INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (1,1,'2015-11-23 09:29:39','2015-11-23 09:29:39','<h3>12 Ways To Ensure That Your Capoeira Teacher Loves You<a href=\"http://www.zumbicdo.com\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-57\" src=\"http://blog.cdoseoul.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/zumbi-blog-100x100px.png\" alt=\"zumbi-blog-100x100px\" width=\"100\" height=\"100\" /></a></h3>\r\nWhat does etiquette have to do with learning Capoeira? Perhaps everything. It was <a href=\"http://www.origensdobrasil.co.uk/bimba.php\">less than 100 years ago</a> that the first Capoeira academy was established by Mestre Bimba. Prior to 1932 Capoeira classes were not advertised or open for public consumption. That means that you could only learn Capoeira if:<!--more-->\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>You were luck enough to find a master.</li>\r\n	<li>That master had the capacity to teach (i.e. possessed the time and facilities).</li>\r\n	<li>The master <strong>agreed</strong> to take you on as a student.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThat means the interpersonal relationship between the master and the student had to be a fairly decent one prior to the 1930s. The knowledge transfer process would require sacrifices on both the part of the teacher and the student.\r\n\r\nIt is important to know that only 100 years ago Capoeira was persecuted. Masters had to make huge personal sacrifices to preserve their art. Consequently, Capoeira teachers tend to be more moody with students and protective of their art than Yoga teachers (for example). Many Capoeira teachers teach Capoeira without really \"teaching\" it.\r\n\r\nI have been practicing Capoeira long enough to have the fortune of being both a student and a teacher. Like my teacher, I will always be a student of Capoeira. Yet, over the years I\'ve made most of the mistakes a beginner makes. Observe the following guidelines to build a relationship with sufficient depth to accelerate learning as a student and ensure that your teacher is really teaching you:\r\n<h5>Timeliness</h5>\r\nBe on time. You might discover that your teacher occasionally shows up late. That\'s how it is sometimes. Regardless, the good student is always on time. <strong>If you are late be sure to call your teacher in advance</strong> to let him or her know. They will really appreciate it and value your courtesy.\r\n<h5>Salutation</h5>\r\nBe sure to say hi to your teacher as soon as you grace them. It is a good practice to <strong>greet all the teachers in the room</strong> if you are in an academy with many teachers.\r\n\r\nIf it is your first class, say your name, age, and prior athletic experience. Try not to show off, but do make a good first impression. The personal information will help the teacher to understand your potential and set the class at the appropriate pace.\r\n\r\nIf you are new to Capoeira or visiting a larger school it may not be easy to identify the teacher of the class you are about to take. In such situations, salute the first person you make eye contact with and ask them if they are teaching the next class. Chances are they will be able to point you to the teacher. If they can\'t repeat the process until you find a student that knows what\'s going on.\r\n\r\nFinally, make your salutation brief as the teacher probably has a million things to think about just before teaching the class. If the teacher seems busy or uninterested don\'t take it personally, they are probably focused on what they have to teach. Save discussion and long introductions for after class when the teacher invites the students to eat or go for a drink.\r\n<h5>Hydration</h5>\r\n<strong>Drink water before and after class.</strong> During class focus on learning Capoeira. Some teachers are more permissive of taking water breaks. Be sure to understand what type of teacher you are dealing with.\r\n<h5>Whites</h5>\r\nCapoeiristas wear white pants and shirts. You must also wear shoes if you practice the \"Angola\" version of Capoeira. Don\'t think you look good in white? Get over it (or choose another hobby).\r\n\r\nMost Capoeira academies have a uniform. That means that they will not only wear white pants, but also ensure that those pants display the school logo. Even the most lenient teachers would tell you that they feel a modicum of pride to see their students in nice <strong>clean whites that show the school logo</strong>.\r\n\r\nFinally, after your first batizado you will be issued with cordão. After that ceremony you are officially a Capoeirista. Your teacher will expect you to behave as such and wear your cordão.\r\n<h5>Silence</h5>\r\nAfter saluting your teacher you will get a good sense of the level of strictness that the teacher practices. To err on the side of caution, <strong>never talk during class.</strong> If you notice other students talking and feel that the atmosphere of the class is very relaxed, venture an expression (or two) and try to gauge the teacher\'s response. If the teacher doesn\'t glare at you only then can you assume that talking in class is permitted.\r\n\r\nNote: Be careful to notice the level of the students that talk in class. Often senior students can do and say anything. The teacher might even appreciate tenured students talking and not following in class. However, the you might not be afforded the same graces as a newbie.\r\n<h5>Follow</h5>\r\nYour job as a new Capoeirista is to follow the class as closely as possible. Follow every last detail you observe. In Capoeira, the devil really is in the detail. Focus as much as you can. You may not understand why you are doing a particular movement for many years. Nonetheless, try not to interrupt the class if you don\'t know why you do something. <strong>Class time is short and it is for movement.</strong> Save philosophical questions for after class when you are eating or drinking with your teacher.\r\n<h5>Question</h5>\r\nIf you absolutely can\'t follow the class, then your job as a new Capoeirista is to question the teacher. This is beneficial to both the student and the teacher. Never be shy to ask questions if you can\'t follow the movement. Teachers, particularly younger teachers, like it when they are asked to demonstrate the movement again. Older teachers may not demonstrate the movement again, but they are certainly happy to walk you through it if they see your keen effort.\r\n\r\n<strong>Avoid asking other students questions during class</strong>, particularly if your teacher is strict.\r\n<h5>Effort</h5>\r\nThis is perhaps the most important thing to observe. <strong>Put all your effort into the class.</strong> Make sure that the teacher notices your effort too. Your effort towards learning and training in class makes all the difference to the teacher. It shows a good attitude. If you don\'t follow the movement precisely but demonstrate that you are trying to the best of your abilities, your teacher is going to try harder to help you overcome the challenges that you are facing.\r\n\r\nPoor effort is often interpreted as having a poor attitude toward learning. Teachers often can\'t help reciprocating with a poor attitude to helping you. So remember that effort is contagious.\r\n<h5>Accept</h5>\r\nAccept that your teacher is not going to be perfect. Accept that they will have behavior that you might not appreciate. Accept that they might not teach you everything that you want to learn and accept that they may not be teaching movement that you like all the time.\r\n\r\nYour job is to learn everything that is being taught that day in class. Try not to pick what you learn. Try not to pick what movements you will put your effort in. <strong>Just train.</strong>\r\n<h5>Socialize</h5>\r\nCapoeira is a social art. <strong>To truly master Capoeira you must do it in community.</strong> Consequently, be sure to socialize with your teacher. Take every opportunity time affords to eat and drink with your teacher (and the other students in your group).\r\n<h5>Farewell</h5>\r\nAlways say goodbye to your teacher. There may be occasions where you have to leave before class or before the social activities after class conclude. If you need to leave before the formal end of the class, be sure to say it at the start of the class and then remind the teacher again when you have to leave. <strong>No matter what, take the time to say adieu.</strong> In Bahia saying \"salve\" is sufficient. In African-American circles departure is performed with an embrace or sequence of hand gestures. Try to observe how others say goodbye to the teacher and conduct yourself in a similar fashion.\r\n<h5>Consistency</h5>\r\nFinally, all of this is irrelevant if you don\'t show up for class on a regular basis. <strong>Be sure that you attend class consistently</strong>, just like you did when you were back in high school. Capoeira teachers don\'t give awards for perfect attendance. However, there is a soft spot in their hearts for the students that are always there.','Class Etiquette','','trash','open','open','','hello-world','','','2015-12-19 03:24:35','2015-12-19 03:24:35','',0,'http://zumbicdo.quilombolaengineering.com/?p=1',0,'post','',1),(2,1,'2015-12-15 09:29:39','2015-12-15 09:29:39','Professor Zumbi hails from the island of Jamaica and leads the Cordão de Ouro Capoeira group in Seoul. Zumbi has practiced and taught Capoeira on every continent since commencing his capoeira voyage in 2000 in Berkeley, California. He is presently planning to teach private classes in Hong Kong and provide introductory courses in Mount Dora, Florida.\r\n\r\nPrior to retiring from the corporate world to teach capoeira professionally, Zumbi was a business development manager at SK Telecom. Zumbi graduated from the Wharton School with an MBA in Marketing. He credits his discplined training and beloved Capoeira community as major contributors to his professional and academic success.\r\n\r\n<blockquote>Capoeira is the intersection of art, discipline, strategy, and philosophy... I teach capoeira to help spread the joy of Capoeira to those young professionals willing to live a life at this intersection.','Professor Zumbi','','publish','closed','open','','sample-page','','','2015-12-19 04:40:00','2015-12-19 04:40:00','',0,'http://zumbicdo.quilombolaengineering.com/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),(4,1,'2015-12-15 09:42:45','2015-12-15 09:42:45','','onetake-orange-header-1920x89','','inherit','open','closed','','onetake-orange-header-1920x89','','','2015-12-15 09:42:45','2015-12-15 09:42:45','',0,'http://zumbicdo.quilombolaengineering.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/onetake-orange-header-1920x89.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(5,1,'2015-12-15 09:47:09','2015-12-15 09:47:09','','cdoseoul-logo-alpha-300x300px','','inherit','open','closed','','cdoseoul-logo-alpha-300x300px','','','2015-12-15 09:47:09','2015-12-15 09:47:09','',0,'http://zumbicdo.quilombolaengineering.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/cdoseoul-logo-alpha-300x300px.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(6,1,'2015-12-15 09:50:10','2015-12-15 09:50:10','','onetake-background','','inherit','open','closed','','onetake-background','','','2015-12-15 09:50:10','2015-12-15 09:50:10','',0,'http://zumbicdo.quilombolaengineering.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/onetake-background.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(7,1,'2015-12-16 05:10:21','2015-12-16 05:10:21','','10958943_1009240749103904_2577027696725228395_o','','inherit','open','closed','','10958943_1009240749103904_2577027696725228395_o','','','2015-12-16 05:10:21','2015-12-16 05:10:21','',0,'http://zumbicdo.quilombolaengineering.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/10958943_1009240749103904_2577027696725228395_o.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8,1,'2015-12-16 05:45:56','2015-12-16 05:45:56','','zumbi-blog-100x100px','','inherit','open','closed','','zumbi-blog-100x100px','','','2015-12-16 05:45:56','2015-12-16 05:45:56','',0,'http://zumbicdo.quilombolaengineering.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/zumbi-blog-100x100px.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(12,1,'2015-12-16 07:04:42','